When using the @Mock annotation from a mocking framework like Mockito in a trying out environment, it&#39;s now not possible to inject a actual dependency directly into the @Mock object. The reason of mocking is to simulate the behavior of dependencies to isolate the unit beneath test. However, you may set up the mock object to go back unique values or behaviors as wanted on your test case.

Here&#39;s an instance of how you could use Mockito to installation behavior for a mocked item:

```
@RunWith(MockitoJUnitRunner.class)
public class MyTest {

    @Mock
    private MyDependency myDependency;

    @Test
    public void myTest() {
        // Setting up a behavior for the mocked dependency
        Mockito.when(myDependency.someMethod()).thenReturn(&quot;Some value&quot;);

        // Your test code that uses the mocked dependency
        
    }
}
```

In the example above, MyDependency is being mocked the use of the `@Mock` annotation. The conduct of the someMethod of MyDependency is described using the Mockito.When and thenReturn methods. This allows you to specify what the method should go back whilst it is called in the course of the test execution.

If you need to check the interplay among the unit below take a look at and a real dependency, you may need to remember using the @InjectMocks annotation at the side of @Mock to mechanically inject the mocked dependencies into the unit beneath check. However, this technique does no longer permit for the injection of real dependencies into a mock.

